3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MEXC calculates funding rates every 8 hours at 00:00, 08:00, and 16:00 UTC using a time-weighted average of the premium between perpetual and spot prices. The exchange applies a symmetric funding fee cap typically ranging from -0.75% to +0.75% per payment period. Zero maker fees on MEXC make it particularly attractive for delta-neutral arbitrage strategies, though the 0.03% taker fee applies to market orders."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","JUP","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"JUP's funding rates tend to spike during Solana ecosystem rallies and major Jupiter protocol updates, creating profitable arbitrage windows. The token's moderate trading volume on MEXC provides sufficient liquidity for medium-sized positions while maintaining reasonable spreads. DeFi governance tokens like JUP often exhibit higher funding rate volatility compared to major cryptocurrencies."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"JUP funding rates on MEXC have shown distinct patterns correlating with Solana network activity and Jupiter protocol milestones. During the January 2024 airdrop period, funding rates consistently exceeded +0.4% per 8-hour period as retail demand surged. The token typically experiences negative funding during broader DeFi sell-offs, creating opportunities for long-biased arbitrageurs. Weekly patterns show higher positive funding rates during US trading hours when DeFi activity peaks."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities and Strategies"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MEXC's zero maker fees create favorable conditions for high-frequency funding rate arbitrage on JUP/USDT. Traders can exploit the 8-hour funding interval by establishing delta-neutral positions 30-60 minutes before payment times when rate predictions solidify. Cross-exchange arbitrage opportunities frequently arise between MEXC and Binance, particularly during Jupiter ecosystem announcements. The relatively thin order book means larger positions (>$50k) may experience higher slippage costs that impact arbitrage profitability."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations and Limitations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"JUP's correlation with Solana network performance introduces systematic risk that pure funding arbitrage cannot hedge. MEXC's aggressive token listing strategy and regulatory uncertainties pose counterparty risks that traders must factor into position sizing. The exchange's order book depth for JUP/USDT remains limited compared to tier-1 exchanges, making large arbitrage positions vulnerable to adverse selection. Auto-deleveraging mechanisms during extreme market moves can force-close profitable funding positions without warning."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"What are typical JUP funding rates on MEXC?","answer":"JUP funding rates on MEXC typically range from -0.2% to +0.6% per 8-hour period, with extreme spikes reaching the ±0.75% cap during high volatility events. Rates tend to be positive during DeFi sector rallies and negative during broader market downturns."},{"question":"How does MEXC's zero maker fee affect JUP arbitrage?","answer":"Zero maker fees significantly improve arbitrage economics by eliminating entry/exit costs for limit orders. This allows profitable arbitrage at lower funding rate thresholds compared to exchanges charging maker fees, though the 0.03% taker fee still applies to market orders."},{"question":"What position sizes work best for JUP funding arbitrage on MEXC?","answer":"Optimal position sizes typically range from $5,000 to $30,000 to balance funding income with market impact costs. Larger positions may face significant slippage due to JUP's relatively thin order book depth on MEXC compared to major exchange pairs."},{"question":"How does JUP funding correlate with Jupiter protocol events?","answer":"JUP funding rates often spike 24-48 hours before major Jupiter protocol updates, governance votes, or partnership announcements as speculative positioning increases. Protocol fee distribution events typically drive sustained positive funding as holders accumulate positions."}]}]
